<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-591-036  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 591 036.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  June 25 1990 v9 n13 p8(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Roeder becomes acting chief after OSDIT shake-up. (William Roeder)(General Services Administration's Office of Software Developmentand Information Technology)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Power, Kevin.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. General Services Administration. Office of SoftwareDevelopment and Information TechnologyResignationExecutiveHiringMIS.andO;Person:    Roeder, William (selection and appointment); Grandier, Howard(resignation, retirement, etc.).andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Roeder Becomes Acting Chief After OSDIT Shake-UpandM;William Roeder was named recently as acting director of the General ServicesAdministration's Office of Software Development and Information Technology(OSDIT).andM;Meanwhile Diane Herdt, director of OSDIT's Software Management SupportDivision, has been reassigned to GSA's Office of Information Systems.andM;Roeder replaces howard Grandier who left GSA earlier this month after aninternal agency investigation alleged OSDIT employees spent agency money on aparty celebrating the opening of the organization's new offices in FallsChurch, Va., in 1988.andP;  GSA sources confirmed the agency's inspector generalhad invetigated the incident and that an internal hearing was held to examineGrandier's and Herdt's role in the matter.andP;  However, sources could notconfirm details of the IG's probe.andM;GSA spokesman Robert Fiser said the agency had no comment on the matter.andO;John Caron, assistant commissioner of GSA's Information Resources ManagementService, also would not comment.andP;  OSDIT falls under IRMS' Office of TechnicalAssistance, which Caron oversees.andM;Roeder had served as director of OSDIT's Federal Information ResourcesManagement Planning.andP;  Caron said there will be a competitive search for a newdirector.andO;</TEXT></DOC>